
Flask App + Docker + Docker Hub (FULL STEP-BY-STEP)
🔹 Step 0: Prerequisites (VERY IMPORTANT)
Make sure you have installed:

Docker Desktop
Python (optional, but useful)
👉 After installing Docker:

Open Docker Desktop
Ensure it says “Docker is running”
🔹 Step 1: Create Project Folder
Create a folder:

flask-docker-app
Inside it create 3 files:

app.py
requirements.txt
Dockerfile
🔹 Step 2: Write Flask App (app.py)
👉 Copy and paste CORRECTED CODE (your given code had formatting errors):

from flask import Flask, render_template_string

app = Flask(__name__)

HTML_TEMPLATE = """
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<title>Flask Docker App</title>
<style>
body {
background: linear-gradient(to right, #00c6ff, #0072ff);
color: white;
font-family: 'Segoe UI', Tahoma, Geneva, Verdana, sans-serif;
text-align: center;
padding-top: 100px;
}
h1 {
font-size: 3em;
margin-bottom: 0.2em;
}
p {
font-size: 1.5em;
}
.card {
background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.1);
padding: 2em;
border-radius: 20px;
box-shadow: 0 0 20px rgba(0,0,0,0.3);
width: 50%;
margin: auto;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>
<div class="card">
<h1>Welcome to Flask + Docker!</h1>
<p>This is a vibrant web page running inside a Docker container.</p>
<p>Change the code → Rebuild → Restart Docker to see updates!</p>
</div>
</body>
</html>
"""

@app.route('/')
def home():
    return render_template_string(HTML_TEMPLATE)

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(host='0.0.0.0', port=5000)
🔹 Step 3: Create requirements.txt
Flask==2.2.5
🔹 Step 4: Create Dockerfile (IMPORTANT FIX)
👉 Your Dockerfile had syntax mistakes. Use this:

FROM python:3.9-slim

WORKDIR /app

COPY requirements.txt .
RUN pip install -r requirements.txt

COPY . .

EXPOSE 5000

CMD ["python", "app.py"]
🔹 Step 5: Open Terminal in Project Folder
👉 Right-click inside folder → Open Terminal / PowerShell

🔹 Step 6: Build Docker Image
docker build -t flask-docker-app .
✔ Wait until build completes

🔹 Step 7: Run Container
Option 1 (Port 5000 free):
docker run -p 5000:5000 flask-docker-app
Option 2 (if error: port already in use):
docker run -p 5050:5000 flask-docker-app
🔹 Step 8: Check Output
👉 Open browser:

http://localhost:5000
OR

http://localhost:5050
✅ You should see:
“Welcome to Flask + Docker!” page

🔹 Step 9: Login to Docker Hub
👉 First create account on:

Docker Hub
Then run:

docker login
Enter:

Username
Password
🔹 Step 10: Tag Image
docker tag flask-docker-app yourusername/flask-docker-app:latest
👉 Replace yourusername with your Docker Hub username

🔹 Step 11: Push to Docker Hub
docker push yourusername/flask-docker-app:latest
✅ Now your image is online

🔹 Step 12: Test Anywhere (IMPORTANT FOR EXAM)
On any system:

docker pull yourusername/flask-docker-app:latest
docker run -p 5050:5000 yourusername/flask-docker-app:latest
Open:

http://localhost:5050
🔥 Common Errors (Exam Tips)
❌ Error: Docker not running
✔ Solution: Start Docker Desktop

❌ Port already in use
✔ Use:

-p 5050:5000
❌ Syntax error in Dockerfile
✔ Ensure:

CMD ["python", "app.py"]
❌ Changes not visible
✔ Always rebuild:

docker build -t flask-docker-app .
🧠 Viva Short Answer (IMPORTANT)
👉 What is Docker?
Docker is a containerization platform used to package applications with dependencies.

👉 What is containerization?
Running applications in isolated environments called containers.

👉 Why Docker Hub?
To store and share Docker images online.

👉 Why expose port 5000?
Flask runs on port 5000, so we map it to host.

